This flooding is over an old jack pine stand. There are numerous channels and islands with downed trees all over. This flooding should be excellent habitat for n. pike y. perch and white suckers, yet no perch or suckers were collected.

Five loons and numerous kingfishers sighted. Fishing reported very poor. Numerous rough fish in population. Lake level is reported up 3' and fish are entering past barrier in out-let. Length-wt frequency data for trout on file at district office.

No trout were taken in set off south shore. Best trout catch was near outlet. Brown stomachs contained leeches, minnows, caddis larvae. One rainbow stomach contained aquatic insect larvae. Length-weight data for all trout and sample of suckers on file at district office. Plankton bloom present.

S.E. run: Observed good year class of BCR 2-4" N.E. run: Observed 1 carp, 3 small BCR, 1 small BLG and several YEP N.W. Pas. run: Observed spottail shiner in fair numbers, some small YEP 78 WAE were seen but not netted in the two nights of shocking

Houghton Lake Association members assisted Mike Phillips, Kyle Kuger, and me in the survey. The lake was moderately turbid but fish were easily observed for netting. A slight to moderate breeze out of the SW was apparent on 10/8/91. The sky was partly cloudy and the air was cool. Conditions were similar on 10/9/91.
From public access site T23NR3WSec34 northWard 2 miles along shoreline up to the Cut River.

Survey Comments: Crew met Mike Mol, DNR Conservation Officer, at East side of Public Access Site @ 7p.m. Concrete ramp, easy to launch. Lake was turbid but fish were visible for netting. Night was clear with 3/4 full moon and lake was flat calm. Only Walleyes were netted and all (87) were scale sampled. Other fish observed included some BCR, NOP, BLG & CWS. Crew shocked for 108 minutes covering two miles of shoreline.
240 V DC Boom-Shocker 18' Alum Boat with 35 h.p. Mercury
Fyke and trap nets were set on south side which is wooded, and gill nets were set near dam in deeper water.
Carp were observed spawning in the upper portion of the lake which is very shallow and very weedy. We request a stocking of both largemouth bass and northern pike because predators are lacking.
